The Ukrainian Parliament today refused the request to abolish, as part of a revision of the Criminal Code, those paragraphs on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Timshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the arrested Prime Minister, rejected the Members at the second reading of the application for a reduction in the penalties for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the conclusion of a supposedly negative contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet final; in December the appeal of the convicted will be brought to trial.
Tymoshenko himself refers to the judgment as the political revenge of the regime, and in the West too the trial led to the suspicion of the court's bias.
The request, paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was sentenced to be removed from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
