V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The original carefree drive is made by a series of completely preventable, dilettantic errors to the routine drive to the early shift.
Although it has been possible to fulfil the ambitions to a large extent, what good is it if no one obviously wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the store tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already-year "Need for Speed" game series back into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he did not actually seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the way the enclosed passages fail, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But the way you're used to it at NFS is, in the end, much different than you expected.
Sure - it is potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some unnecessary errors that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are no longer mistakes, but rather signs of an incomprehensible folly of the game developers in principle.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole range of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty single races.
This means that each race is carried out on a different route and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don't have a moment to feel that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still very pretty, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the journey through the desert, through the autumn landscape or high above through deep snowy landscape works visually very pleasant.
From time to time untypical elements bring a little change in the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that greatly restricts the view.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stop watch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And that's what the police are involved in, trying to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages where Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack escapes from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are much less such passages in the game than you would expect (in fact only three).
In the end, this is more to the advantage, because this element has at least no chance of becoming boring - it is in the context of the above mentioned one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model passes in the footboards of the previous parts.
In other words, from the point of view of today, it does not tear out trees, on the other hand it could not be said that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model continues to be quite fair to an action-loaded race, even though one could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems only occur after some time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not entirely O.K.
From a game of this kind it is hardly expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no impact on any object know how the car behaves, then obviously it's not all right.
Typical example: When moving close to the front or to the front of the front of the car, one "strives" the other cars in some places only easily, but in other, almost identical situation you get into the sludges and turns wild pirouettes.
Or drive the car to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter any more, it's all very annoying.
The restarts are so solved: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last point of the line.
Only - in every race you only have five restarts.
When you've exhausted them, everything starts from the beginning.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't work out, but you better not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the restart does not even help, there is nothing to help but to learn the critical section from the head.
It is very unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, need to be run in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Otherwise, "civil" cars are always met in the same configuration at the appropriate location, whether you are the first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the contestant passes by two coming cars before a play, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The competitors have other advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent at the same place and again here without regard to the time.
This is the most crazy thing to do at the end of the game on the long bridge that you happen in the opposite direction.
The contestant has to get you out of here on the devil.
And when he's in front of you, he takes the view, of course, so that you drive your own car a few times in the first place.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly gives you the joy of the game.
And that's a shame, because despite a simpler driving model, the game as a whole is quite entertaining and, on the other hand, so much so that you don't know where your head is.
And in principle, no matter what "debt" is to it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that cannot cause boredom, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car in the course of the races.
You must not miss the gas stations on the line, because right here you can change the car, although in most cases the car that you have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight motorways and exotic super sports cars for the technical journeys, for example on the serpentine in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game history also goes the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual locations that you know from history.
Here there are not only medals, but also points of experience for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and the history.
To get to the higher driver level, various objects must be opened: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also connected to the online autologous function, which, among other things, compares its own results with those of other players and also provides additional collective functions.
One of other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
This is where you get to a subway tunnel (because of me) by car, where you run long in the dark on the tracks (because of me).
On the tacho there are numbers between 150 a 200 km / h (because of me), but there comes a subway from the back and drives a uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial group, we will probably have a long time to argue about whether this was a blackout of the game design or whether the authors think we're so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
It is all the more annoying that in some exciting moments the frequency of the image is slowing down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
This is, however, particularly the case of accidents with a greater number of persons involved, where a continuous FPS is of no use to you anyway.
The sound is as far as O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to address a scale as wide as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá "was created by everyone something" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are more mixed.
If the game was not reduced by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary errors, we could have argued with the chest tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game looks kind of unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared to see that these mistakes are stabbing into your eyes with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "students of the collective revolution" with singing ensembles of the Charles University
The Festa Academica Festival now offers for the third time the quickening of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Samten Revolution and this, including the music experience.
During the course of the festival, the twenty professional and university chors will present themselves.
The festival will focus on the two concerts that will take place on November 17.
"The University of Charles has a great share of the festival."
"Among the participants, the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanist Studies is also represented and, among other things, the Rector Václav Hampl is in the festival committee," led the head of the organization team, Jakub Čaloun.
