The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded a hundred years ago in New York, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabling Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was only taken over in 1924 - it was originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM laid the merger of four companies, the history of which dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous card watches to register the start and end of the work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who was also the chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
