Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, the ČSSR had only five approved state travel agencies: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the travel agencies were only selling travel to the socialist East Bloc countries, and in the West they were allowed only to choose.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one could also travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even citizens of the Eastern bloc (including the Czechoslovakia) allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of the Czech Republic wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then they had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the way things had gone.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
The vast majority of the Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that still lasts today.
The collective revolution of 1989 followed a rice revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which is no longer known today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country in the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation was abolished in the neighbouring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers were sleeping on a trip to Paris in the tent in the park, because who would have had the money to stay in the hotel or in a pension at the time.
A typical feature of Czechs abroad was a trunk packed with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our level of living and therefore the average salaries increased, which in 1997 ended up in another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips through charter flights after 1997, making the flights incredibly cheap in comparison to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had unsolicited payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-collected" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was taken to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying every year in far-away sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations are being flown directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 000 Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch, which marked our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely brought our country into line with the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 000 CZK per head for a single holiday, including the cost of the holiday place.
