The low temperatures in February did not only cause losses in the level of millions in agriculture, but also limited the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6% in the first quarter of the year. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16%, which has a brake effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustainable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The fall in economic activity to November has continued to increase unemployment in the Mexican state. In the first quarter, the Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment, since from January to March, 55 053 people in Sinaloa had no employment, which is 4.53% of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% and from July to 6.19%, which resulted in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in the year dates back to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments, the policy of the public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently watching is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, the loss of liquidity on the market as a result of the cuts in funds by the legislation that was adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy for those who are prohibitively raising dollars to make them work for themselves, to invest it or to use it for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
