"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, due to the problems of entry and, on the one hand, because it is difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work here, which is what makes unemployment rise," he says.
Black labour
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38% of the people working in the country who do not pay in the social security funds.
In the case of unemployment and undeclared work, low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, in accordance with the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Agency for Labour and Social Care in Mexico), come.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the reduction in economic activity and the growing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) over the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was 630 597 dollars from January to June, which represents a gap of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development), for its part, has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, the national government requested a loan of 3 000 000 million pesos at the National Congress in July to reinvest the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
The first year of the government, Mario López Valdé, made it clear to the representatives of entrepreneurship that the government was incompetent.
