The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its twenty-year existence
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is realized"
In the exclusive conversation with Viva, the bass player Jeff Ament from Pearl Jam says that the band is prepared to give one of its best concerts the next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They were expected for more than 20 years, but the band assures that a dream will come true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
This was assured by the bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is located in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their twenty years of existence and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On that day they will be in the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You will read an extract from the conversation, whose full copy can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costarican fans, a dream is realized when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: are you aware of what this means to your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is also realized for us.
This is just the second time that we have played in South and Central America, and so far it has been great.
I've only been on vacation in Costa Rica once. It's such a beautiful country that we'll probably stay there for a few more days.
It's exciting for us to take our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely complete. They experience the days before the concert most intensively.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry for taking so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn't that a little pressure from your visit?
Some of the most great shows we've done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on a few huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are thrilled by the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you meet Costa Rica and his waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua for surfing. Together with Mexico, the excellent areas are for surfing. In this way, we have learned about people who love surfing.
With a view of the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the Costa Rica event?
Since we've never played there, we don't sit down.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that is partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes another song so that the decision that we will play will not be easy.
If we take two or three songs that we have not played for a long time into the repertoire, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they might become forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why it's for the audience.
With this tour you will celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years.
We also continue to focus on this blessing and like to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited to produce music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't stand better.
What did it mean for you to take an active part in the birth of the Grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We're good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement comes out of a group of friends.
Every now and then a band comes out of a city, but it is already unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud of it and are honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw soundgarden on their tour. We are still happy to be friends with all of them and it honors us to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago. This alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we are all happy to be alive and we are also taking care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened, which give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One person trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship to fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you feel about a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to miss this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you think that people have come because of the music, that reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what they have created without being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never published a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us, friends. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, to laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas is responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, in particular Eddie Vedder, and that's why the band chose to open it?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and this band we liked best. That's why we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. This will certainly be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He's singing it, and I think he's singing the first thing he can think of.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
Of so many +
One of the first to come to my mind is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk about the bassist I like all afternoon.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion appearance?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word "grunge."
When I think about it, I think of the bands that I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it's great, because it's worth listening to these music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she's more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that could be a little bit easy to do, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in them.
The tears came to me when I heard Ed play them. They are very dark songs.
I believe that when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example, if you lose a family member or a friend - that affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody this for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
