Fujimori came back to the hospital for medical examinations
The former president Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, informed his family doctor.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is in prison for the violation of human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which operates four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of the Congress and his personal doctor, told the TV that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and loss of muscle in the lower body parts.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not wish that because he thought he was innocent.
He was operated four times on tongue cancer and he lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood flow problems in the legs, were included by the doctor.
Since September 2007, Fujimori has been in the detention centre of Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squadron of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official secondment, led by the Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. According to the Uruguayan President, this will be the highlight of his booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of the Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both Presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the President of the South American country announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is looking for the support of Calderón in terms of the incident with France, when the French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
