Mexico has been in the chair of the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double assessment with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the implementation of tax information exchange agreements in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which include countries that have not introduced all the international standards for tax cooperation.
A free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place at the business level since 2004, which has contributed to the growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
