The secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome provides details of the aircraft accident in which the government secretary Francisco Blake and another seven people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communication and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation into the accident in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and other seven people were killed indicate that the helicopter, with its whole unbroken structure, was directly hit against the ground without the pilot being able to launch an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communication and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before the start that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing had contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing the hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had several ground contacts."
He also stated that the helicopter was built for 19 inmates, which is why he fulfilled all the conditions for the transport of the staff.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found in the investigations in the area where the machine had come down.
"No aircraft parts were found in the search at other places, the impact on the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why he met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a range of 7 to 30 degrees.
At the moment, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but it could take several months, perhaps even a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Assistance Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidential had flown at a speed of travel and that the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information strengthens the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the Head of SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be taken into account in the investigation:
Visibility:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of the visual flight. This means that the team should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded appropriate weather conditions at the start. During the further flight in the direction of the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State some deep hanging clouds were raised.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca valley because of the clouds.
The impact site:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter match. There may not have been a loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available up to the present time indicates that the helicopter was hit from a straight and a side direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggest that the helicopter was hit on the ground with its undamaged structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the accident site do not indicate either fire or explosion.
The latest results indicate several ground contacts.
In the on-site studies, aircraft parts were found at a height of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is slippery and has a gradient of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably went to break.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a minor search in an area that went beyond the restricted area at the site of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the unbroken aircraft structure had hit the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol to find the gene for obesity
She has a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and young people, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Security Institute of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth," with which the genetic markers are to be found in connection with overweight.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry Focus) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team, consisting of doctors, nurses, food specialists and social workers, was built.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports grounds of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday from 8: 00.
He stressed that the study began at the Cuauhtémoc sports square (in the west of the state of México) and has been continued on the sports square of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México) since 8 October.
When the target of 500 to 600 research staff is reached, the study will be continued at the Independencia sports course (in the south of the capital district) and completed by Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He said that the aim of the study was to get to know the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify the risk factors of Mexican children and young people in the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
