In his lecture "Schlaglöcher from a technical point of view," which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible developed the asphalt with polymers modified in order to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which however has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of the road floor and thus avoid the occurrence of slums.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together they give the road surface its characteristic numerical behaviour.
The numerical behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180 ° C as a liquid, at 120 ° C it is very tether-liquid and at 50 ° C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes on one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ's researcher noticed that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible road surface, which consisted of six material layers, of which the last three were asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small, in asphalt, and then fortified stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer, had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on to it and the forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of power in the street.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he said, "a last layer is designed, the so-called carrying layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it has to make friction.
The one that receives and distributes most of the forces, the carrying layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be taken into account, especially the water, "he said," because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water enters the layer and it is difficult to get back out. This causes a softening of all the layers of the road surface and therefore the appearance of slums.
When a whipped bell is created, "he said," the cover layer will be removed first, while the wear layer will only be affected after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained in the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs. "
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico's National Research System) said that the vehicle load was another important cause of the occurrence of slurry holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road load should always be in relation to the load of the vehicle and it should be ensured that, in order to avoid frequent slurry holes, this regulation is complied with.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be easily repaired without the use of high temperatures.
